WEBVTT

00:00:01.000 --> 00:00:05.000
Hi, everyone. Thanks for joining us today from all over the world.

00:00:05.000 --> 00:00:11.000
My name is Alex Chisholm. I'm a product manager here at Posit working on hosted data science platforms.

00:00:11.000 --> 00:00:20.000
In our session today, I'm really excited to be giving an overview of our new hosted data publishing solution called Connect Cloud.

00:00:20.000 --> 00:00:24.000
So what I want to be able to do today is both show you what the tool looks like,

00:00:24.000 --> 00:00:32.000
get up and running with a few example workflows, and then take any questions that you might be having for those who have already interacted with it.

00:00:32.000 --> 00:00:38.000
If you haven't played around just yet, I do encourage you to go to Posit.Connect.Cloud.

00:00:38.000 --> 00:00:43.000
You can create a free account and you can start publishing your work.

00:00:43.000 --> 00:00:50.000
This is an alpha release. I think we started promoting this new platform in the middle of July.

00:00:50.000 --> 00:00:54.000
There's a very specific workflow that we're going to talk about today.

00:00:54.000 --> 00:00:58.000
And the first thing is like it's all GitHub centric in nature right now.

00:00:58.000 --> 00:01:06.000
So we're essentially taking code and public GitHub repos, and we're going to be able to deploy or publish the code and the projects that you have.

00:01:06.000 --> 00:01:12.000
And then you're going to get a shareable URL that is also public in nature.

00:01:12.000 --> 00:01:21.000
So the one requirement to create an account right now is having a GitHub account, and that's going to be how you authenticate through the platform.

00:01:21.000 --> 00:01:29.000
And taking a step back, like I know there are many things that you can build today in terms of taking data,

00:01:29.000 --> 00:01:36.000
maybe putting models together, being able to put reporting out or building dashboards and applications.

00:01:36.000 --> 00:01:44.000
I'm curious if anybody on the call builds other things than these that are shown on the screen right now, what those might be.

00:01:44.000 --> 00:01:51.000
But these are the seven frameworks that the alpha version of Connect Cloud currently supports.

00:01:51.000 --> 00:01:55.000
So we have four applications from Shiny, Streamlit, Dash, and Bokeh.

00:01:55.000 --> 00:02:02.000
And then on the document side, you can publish Cordo documents, our Markdown documents, and Jupyter notebooks.

00:02:02.000 --> 00:02:15.000
Over time, we will be adding on to what is supported on the system, which is why it's so valuable for us to understand the other frameworks that you might be using in your day-to-day work.

00:02:15.000 --> 00:02:22.000
So it is relatively, I think, easy these days to build in a lot of different frameworks because there are so many available.

00:02:22.000 --> 00:02:26.000
There's so many great tutorials and resources and documentation that are out there.

00:02:26.000 --> 00:02:31.000
We think that also, though, the sharing of your work should also be easy.

00:02:31.000 --> 00:02:36.000
And I know for myself and my own data science background, this isn't always the case.

00:02:36.000 --> 00:02:48.000
And sometimes it can feel pretty complex to be able to get your working application off of your local environment and onto the laptop or the desktop or whatever of somebody who you want to engage with it.

00:02:49.000 --> 00:03:06.000
So when we were putting together Connect Cloud and acknowledging that we have shinyapps.io and rpubs and cordopub, they all sort of have a very IDE-specific way that you're being able to deploy or publish these applications and documents.

00:03:06.000 --> 00:03:21.000
We wanted to think of something that was unified across both R and Python and that wouldn't require a user to learn about a plugin we might have somewhere, to learn about a new package that they might need to install and work into their actual code potentially.

00:03:21.000 --> 00:03:27.000
So we came up with a sort of three simple steps for this alpha release.

00:03:27.000 --> 00:03:32.000
And this obviously doesn't mean that this is going to be the only way that you can publish forever on Connect Cloud.

00:03:32.000 --> 00:03:34.000
It's just the starting point that we have right now.

00:03:34.000 --> 00:03:38.000
And what we tried to set off to do is you have three simple steps.

00:03:38.000 --> 00:03:45.000
And our hope is that within three minutes, you're going to be able to create a new account, again, through this GitHub authentication.

00:03:45.000 --> 00:03:52.000
You're going to be able to point the platform to one of your public repos with the source code for what it is you want to publish.

00:03:52.000 --> 00:03:54.000
And then you're going to press go.

00:03:54.000 --> 00:04:11.000
And then if we do our job right, we're going to be able to take your code, your dependency files, be able to spin up a working URL that is public in nature that you can start sharing on LinkedIn or with friends, family, whoever it might be.

00:04:11.000 --> 00:04:15.000
And what comes at the end of this process, as I mentioned, is the shareable public URL.

00:04:15.000 --> 00:04:20.000
So this could be an example Quarto dashboard that was put together.

00:04:20.000 --> 00:04:22.000
We're able to deploy it.

00:04:22.000 --> 00:04:24.000
There's a URL associated with it.

00:04:24.000 --> 00:04:30.000
And we'll get into this within the demo in terms of how you as the publisher might interact with some of this.

00:04:30.000 --> 00:04:45.000
One neat thing that we've done on Connect Cloud is this then ties back to a portfolio, in essence, a public portfolio of all the diverse type of work that you've put together.

00:04:45.000 --> 00:04:52.000
So this specific thing that I might have published called economic trends is going to end up back on your portfolio or your profile.

00:04:52.000 --> 00:04:54.000
I mean, you can see economic trends here.

00:04:54.000 --> 00:04:56.000
This is the view for you, the user.

00:04:56.000 --> 00:04:58.000
So you still have controls over things.

00:04:58.000 --> 00:05:08.000
But if you were to share this URL out with others, they'd also be able to see what you're working on and find out a little bit more about you.

00:05:08.000 --> 00:05:12.000
A quick note before we get into the demo portion of today.

00:05:12.000 --> 00:05:24.000
So one way that we need to consider the deployment or the publishing of what you're giving us is for us to know what the system needs to replicate what you did locally.

00:05:24.000 --> 00:05:31.000
So the way that we're able to handle this GitHub workflow, we need a little bit of information about that environment.

00:05:31.000 --> 00:05:42.000
And starting with our projects or our applications in the example that we'll look at today, we need this manifest.json file to be in that public repo.

00:05:42.000 --> 00:05:50.000
I know that many people who haven't worked within Connect before or maybe published from the command line to our other tools might not be familiar with this.

00:05:50.000 --> 00:05:53.000
Thankfully, it just takes one function, write manifest.

00:05:53.000 --> 00:05:56.000
You point to where that application, for instance, might be.

00:05:56.000 --> 00:05:59.000
And it's going to give you this file that we'll look at in one of our examples.

00:05:59.000 --> 00:06:06.000
And this is going to tell Connect Cloud the right packages that we should be installing and the right versions.

00:06:06.000 --> 00:06:16.000
And on the R side of things, it's also going to tell us the R version that you were using locally that we're going to be able to spin up on Connect Cloud.

00:06:16.000 --> 00:06:21.000
If you're working on a Python application, here we're going to use a requirements.txt file.

00:06:21.000 --> 00:06:25.000
So this is what's going to be required in that repo.

00:06:26.000 --> 00:06:30.000
There are a couple of different ways that you can put together this file when working with Python.

00:06:30.000 --> 00:06:37.000
One, you could just create a blank text file, requirements.txt, and add in your dependencies line by line.

00:06:37.000 --> 00:06:41.000
So you need pandas, you need matplotlib, and you could leave it like that if you wanted to.

00:06:41.000 --> 00:06:49.000
Another approach is using pip freeze from the terminal and then spitting this out into a requirements.txt file.

00:06:49.000 --> 00:06:59.000
This will take all of the packages that you're using to run this thing locally and put that into a very specific requirements.txt file that we can take to upload.

00:06:59.000 --> 00:07:08.000
So one difference between the R side and the Python side at the moment is that this manifest file does both the R version and the packages.

00:07:08.000 --> 00:07:15.000
The requirements file only is focused on packages, and you're going to set that Python version from the UI itself.

